7. Failure scenarios to mention in your document

Filebeat failure

If Filebeat cannot read the access log or parse the line correctly, then action mapping and document ID extraction will fail. The document’s Filebeat flow depends on the raw log format being readable. 

CDC failure

If CDC does not capture a database change, the workflow event will not appear in the process event stream. The CDC document says WORKFLOW_HISTORY is the primary source of truth, so missing CDC means missing workflow visibility. 

NiFi failure

If NiFi fails while transforming or enriching the data, the event may not be written to Elasticsearch. Since NiFi is the normalization layer, its failure breaks the pipeline between source and ELK.

Duplicate event risk

If both WORKFLOW_HISTORY and DOCUMENT_QUEUE are used together, the same action may appear twice. The CDC document recommends starting with WORKFLOW_HISTORY only to avoid duplication. 


---

8. Negative scenarios to cover

Access log exists but no database change

A user may click something and the access log will show it, but the database action may fail later. The zero-code document says access logs can capture failed actions even when the DB does not change. 

Database change exists but no user log

Some system actions or background jobs may appear only in CDC and not in access logs. The document says system-account actions may show up as system-initiated events. 

Missing schema name

The CDC document says a schema name must be included when documents move across workflows. Without it, cross-schema tracking becomes unclear. 


